# MASTER PROMPT — MTK STOREFRONT BUILDER

Act as a senior Vanilla JavaScript component architect and production UI engineer.

Build a complete reusable storefront application named `mtk-storefront` for selling hand-painted artwork.

Use this repository as the base: https://github.com/NYCMEL/nala-website.git
Use all wc code for include, subscribe etc from this file: https://github.com/NYCMEL/melify-new/blob/main/js/wc.js 

---

# OUTPUT RULES

* Return ONLY one downloadable ZIP file named exactly: `x.zip`
* Never show code in chat
* Never return patch files or diffs
* Always return complete files only
* Never modify anything outside the scope of this request
* Never generate placeholder explanations instead of files
* Never create images unless explicitly requested

---

# REQUIRED FILES

Generate exactly these files:

* mtk-storefront.config.js
* mtk-storefront.scss
* mtk-storefront.html
* mtk-storefront.js
* index.html
* server/server.js
* server/package.json
* server/mtk-storefront.sqlite

Only create additional files if absolutely required for functionality.

---

# CORE TECH RULES

* Vanilla JavaScript only
* No frameworks
* No Bootstrap
* No React
* No Vue
* No Angular
* No external libraries
* No inline JavaScript
* No inline styles
* SCSS only
* Never compile CSS
* Never use iframes
* Use: `<wc-include href="..."></wc-include>`

---

# COMPONENT ARCHITECTURE

Component wrapper:

```html
<mtk-storefront class="mtk-storefront"></mtk-storefront>
```

Rules:

* Root class must be `.mtk-storefront`
* Scope ALL styles under `.mtk-storefront`
* No global styles
* No global IDs
* Use semantic HTML only
* ADA compliant
* Keyboard accessible
* Visible focus states required

---

# CONFIG + DATA RULES

ALL UI-driven data MUST come from:
`mtk-storefront.config.js`

Paintings must support:

* title
* description
* image
* price
* availability
* dimensions
* medium
* category
* PayPal data

Store owner must be able to:

* change paintings
* change prices
* change availability
* change images
* change details
  from either:
* config file
* SQLite database

---

# EVENT SYSTEM RULES

Wait for `<mtk-storefront>` to exist before initializing because it may load dynamically through `<wc-include>`.

Requirements:

* Subscribe to all `4-mtk-storefront` events using `wc.subscribe`
* Create `onMessage()` handler
* Publish actions using `wc.publish`
* Log ALL payloads using `wc.log` BEFORE publishing

---

# STOREFRONT UI

Header title:
`Madam Mina's Artwork`

Layout requirements:

* `.mtk-storefront` background = `#FFF`
* `.mtk-storefront__shell`

  * `max-inline-size: 1200px`

Home screen:

* display painting cards only
* NO buttons on cards

Painting click behavior:

* opens full-page detail view
* detail view includes:

  * image
  * title
  * description
  * price
  * availability
  * dimensions
  * medium
  * actions
* include circular close button with “X”

---

# SALES + REQUEST FLOWS

## Available Paintings

Show:

* Buy with PayPal
* “Make a counter offer” link

Behavior:

* clicking link reveals counter-offer form
* form hidden by default

## Unavailable Paintings

Show:

* “Request a similar painting” link

Behavior:

* clicking link reveals request form
* form hidden by default

---

# FORM DESIGN RULES

Use Material Design styling for:

* floating labels
* buttons
* fields
* spacing
* focus states
* hover states
* accessibility states

Forms must feel modern and production-ready.

---

# ADMIN FEATURES

Customers:

* NO login required

Admin:

* login visible ONLY when admin chooses to manage/edit

Temporary credentials:

* username: admin
* password: test

Admin capabilities:

* add paintings
* edit paintings
* remove paintings
* persist changes to SQLite

---

# BACKEND RULES

Use:

* Node.js ONLY
* NEVER PHP

Backend folder MUST be:
`server`

Use SQLite to store:

* paintings
* prices
* availability
* offers
* similar-painting requests

Required API endpoints:

* paintings
* offers
* requests

PayPal seller email MUST be configurable in:
`mtk-storefront.config.js`

---

# FAILURE PREVENTION RULES

DO NOT:

* use placeholder code
* omit required files
* generate partial implementations
* break existing requirements
* replace Vanilla JS with frameworks
* compile SCSS into CSS
* expose passwords in UI
* create empty SQLite DB structure without tables
* create fake API routes

Ensure ALL generated files are runnable together.

